MSFT, JNJ and WMT or MCD might be some stocks to look into. They all offer decent growth and good dividends (well, MSFT's dividend is good compared to other tech companies). Other than that adding to your existing positions is a good move too.

Regarding more speculative long term risk, if TSLA drops again it might be worth considering. Not sure what other companies I'd put in that same category. Airlines/Hotels/Casinos are a riskier play and have potential to bounce back over the next few years but they aren't industries I'd want to hold long term personally.

author: CallLivesMatter
body:
Want to get even more granular? Find the companies that did the fewest buybacks and had the most genuine organic growth. Those are the names to *not* bet against. 

Now go find the buyback kings (looking at you TXN) and buy puts on them all the way down. Anyone who used massive buybacks to paper over their huge executive comp? Puts. Anyone who borrowed (with their borderline bullshit BBB rating) to do their buybacks? Puts. Anyone who kept their BBB rating for years, despite having enough cash flow to pay down debt and get a better rating? Puts. 

The BBB thing is a longer story and none of you will read it anyway, but it’s a big deal that we’ll start noticing in the coming months.

Picked a hell of a time to start stock picking didn’t you? Anyway welcome to dividend investing.

Personally what I watch like a hawk atm is the debt of companies and how hard/easy it is for them to service said debt. I mean who knows where we will be a month from now? Surely having a healthy balance sheet can’t hurt though can it?

So here are a couple stock I like:

-	SWKS Hardly any debt, supplier of 4g and future 5g equipment.
-	MSFT Well diversified, debt covered nicely by cash and Cashflow.
-	TXN Quite the market leader, good balance sheet.
-	AAPL Quite expensive atm, but good candidate to buy in a couple shares here and there. 60 billion free Cashflow is ... yeah.

That’s tech. Aka the bubble as some call it. Here are some interesting stocks that are going through even more interesting times:

-	JNJ Good stock, safe ship.
-	MCD Not about the burgers, it’s a play on real estate.
-	DIS Some fairly large brands, Star Wars, ESPN, Disney itself, more likely to become bigger than smaller.
-	3M & CAT Necessary stuff.
-	XOM Most competitors seem on the cusp of bankruptcy, long term good. Maybe wait for a cut, or not.
-	BRK.B Not a dividend payer ... yet.

body:
Want to get even more granular? Find the companies that did the fewest buybacks and had the most genuine organic growth. Those are the names to *not* bet against. 

Now go find the buyback kings (looking at you TXN) and buy puts on them all the way down. Anyone who used massive buybacks to paper over their huge executive comp? Puts. Anyone who borrowed (with their borderline bullshit BBB rating) to do their buybacks? Puts. Anyone who kept their BBB rating for years, despite having enough cash flow to pay down debt and get a better rating? Puts. 

The BBB thing is a longer story and none of you will read it anyway, but it’s a big deal that we’ll start noticing in the coming months.
